{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011QWuxrsqygbR1g6Smyi23Z","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 8 Failure Analysis\n     2→\n     3→## Failures\n     4→\n     5→### 1. `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` → `''`\n     6→\n     7→**Input structure:**\n     8→```\n     9→Line 1: \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\"\n    10→Line 2: \"& Coriander\"\n    11→Line 3: (long body text paragraph)\n    12→...\n    13→Lines 4+: ingredients starting with numbers, long body text\n    14→```\n    15→\n    16→**What the algorithm does:**\n    17→The pre-merge step in `buildCandidates` correctly identifies \"& Coriander\" as a continuation line (starts with `&`) and merges it with the preceding line, producing the single candidate \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\". This candidate passes all hard filters: 54 chars (under 80), no measurement patterns, no metadata pattern, not garbled.\n    18→\n    19→**Why it fails — embedding scoring:**\n    20→The merged title contains ingredient-like terms (\"Harissa Tomato Sauce\", \"Feta\") that increase cosine similarity to `HEADER_REFERENCE` (\"ingredients list, cooking directions, section heading\"). If `headerSim >= titleSim`, then `rawScore = titleSim - max(headerSim, noiseSim) <= 0`. With no `allCapsBonus` (mixed-case) and no `structuralBonus` (not structural heading), the final score `rawScore * 1.12` can fall below the 0.08 minimum threshold. The candidate is filtered out, and `selected` becomes empty, returning `undefined`/`''`.\n    21→\n    22→The code even comments on line 413: \"the pre-merge step above already handles the common Baked Eggs case\" — yet the candidate is silently discarded in scoring. The hard filters pass but the threshold gate fails.\n    23→\n    24→**Root cause:** Descriptive recipe titles containing ingredient names (sauces, cheeses, spices) are penalised by the HEADER_REFERENCE because ingredient words pull the embedding toward the ingredient-list reference rather than the title reference. There is no floor or fallback for a candidate that passes all hard filters and is the only candidate in the pool.\n    25→\n    26→---\n    27→\n    28→### 2. `Faszerowana papryka` → `'PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM'`\n    29→\n    30→**Input structure:**\n    31→```\n    32→Line 1: \"Faszerowana papryka\"   (Polish title)\n    33→Line 2: \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\"  (ALL_CAPS Korean-romanised subtitle)\n    34→Line 3: \"파프리카 계란찜\"           (Korean script — filtered by isLikelyGarbled: letters.length < 2)\n    35→Line 4: (Polish body text, starts lowercase → filtered)\n    36→```\n    37→\n    38→**What the algorithm does:**\n    39→Both \"Faszerowana papryka\" and \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" pass hard filters:\n    40→- \"Faszerowana papryka\": 19 chars, starts uppercase, Polish vowel ratio ~0.44, no measurements. Passes.\n    41→- \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\": ALL_CAPS, `isStructuralHeading` qualifies it (≥2 sig words, each ≥4 alpha chars).\n    42→\n    43→In scoring, \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" receives `+0.08` allCapsBonus + `+0.10` structuralBonus = `+0.18` on top of its rawScore. \"Faszerowana papryka\" receives neither bonus.\n    44→\n    45→**Why the first-line protection fails:**\n    46→The algorithm has an explicit guard (lines 468–479) for exactly this pattern: \"mixed-case title at position 0 followed by a single ALL_CAPS subtitle\". The guard correctly identifies `pos0 = selected.find(s => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text))` and `allCapsCandidates.length === 1` at position 1.\n    47→\n    48→But the guard has a precondition: both candidates must already be in `selected` (i.e., both must have passed the threshold filter). The protection fires *after* the threshold filter, not before it.\n    49→\n    50→If \"Faszerowana papryka\" scores below threshold — which is plausible because:\n    51→- TITLE_REFERENCE is English; a short Polish phrase has lower cosine similarity to it\n    52→- The threshold is inflated to `bestThresholdScore * 0.7` where `bestThresholdScore` comes from \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\"'s strong score (+0.18 bonuses)\n    53→\n    54→...then \"Faszerowana papryka\" never enters `selected`, `pos0 = null`, and the protection is never triggered. The result is \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" alone.\n    55→\n    56→**Root cause:** The first-line protection has a self-defeating design: it only activates when the correct first-line title has *already* survived the threshold independently. When the ALL_CAPS candidate inflates the threshold (via its bonuses) to a level the mixed-case title can't reach, the protection becomes a no-op. The protection is needed most precisely when the mixed-case title is outscored — but that is also when it cannot fire.\n    57→\n    58→---\n    59→\n    60→## Common Themes\n    61→\n    62→### A. ALL_CAPS bias undermines correct mixed-case titles in bilingual recipes\n    63→The `+0.08` allCapsBonus and `+0.10` structuralBonus create a 0.18-point advantage for ALL_CAPS candidates. In bilingual cookbooks where the primary-language title is mixed-case and an ALL_CAPS romanisation or translation follows on the next line, this bonus systematically elevates the secondary subtitle over the actual title. The first-line protection was designed to compensate but fails when the all-caps advantage raises the threshold beyond the mixed-case title's reach.\n    64→\n    65→### B. The first-line protection is a post-hoc bandage that depends on the problem it's meant to solve\n    66→The guard on lines 468–479 requires both candidates to be in `selected` before it can act. Its precondition — `pos0.score >= threshold` — means it only fires when the mixed-case title didn't need the protection in the first place. When the mixed-case title is genuinely outscored by the ALL_CAPS candidate (the case the protection targets), the guard silently skips, making it ineffective.\n    67→\n    68→### C. Ingredient-bearing recipe titles are penalised by the HEADER_REFERENCE\n    69→Recipes named after their key components (e.g. \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\") have titles that semantically overlap with ingredient-list vocabulary. The embedding scorer cannot distinguish \"this is the name of a dish that contains these ingredients\" from \"this is a fragment of an ingredient list\". The rawScore formula `titleSim - max(headerSim, noiseSim)` provides no floor for candidates that pass all structural filters, meaning a legitimate title with modest differentiation can fall below threshold entirely.\n    70→\n    71→### D. No fallback when the candidate pool is unambiguous\n    72→When there is exactly one candidate (or one dominant candidate that clearly passes all hard filters), the threshold mechanism can still discard it if the embedding similarity difference is too small. There is no \"if only one candidate exists and it passed all structural filters, return it\" safety net.\n    73→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0144PXmjEmy913inJ4U8ScKn","session_id":"3e5c8568-eb2f-4e0e-8771-787e6907f7e7","uuid":"00daf5c1-966b-47a4-9705-2db3aae8a3b5"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014BkSXjaPP6uAMyQjqn5dpJ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 9 Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Summary\n     4→\n     5→Two failures, two distinct root causes that share a common theme: the threshold gate has absolute veto power over candidates that pass all structural/hard filters, with no fallback when the candidate pool is small or the positional signal is unambiguous.\n     6→\n     7→The fixes are:\n     8→\n     9→1. **Pre-threshold bilingual protection** — move first-line detection before threshold filtering so ALL_CAPS bonuses can't inflate the threshold beyond the mixed-case title's reach.\n    10→2. **Empty-pool fallback** — when threshold filtering discards every candidate, fall back to the best positional candidate from the hard-filter-passing pool.\n    11→\n    12→These are complementary: fix 1 prevents failure 2 (Faszerowana papryka) by keeping the correct candidate in `selected`; fix 2 prevents failure 1 (Baked Eggs) by ensuring a sole survivor is never silently discarded.\n    13→\n    14→---\n    15→\n    16→## Failure 1: \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" → `''`\n    17→\n    18→### Root Cause\n    19→\n    20→The pre-merge step correctly produces the full candidate. It passes all hard filters (54 chars, no measurements, no metadata, not garbled). But the embedding scorer computes `rawScore = titleSim - max(headerSim, noiseSim)` and because ingredient words (Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce, Coriander) are semantically close to `HEADER_REFERENCE` (\"ingredients list, cooking directions\"), `headerSim ≈ titleSim` or `headerSim > titleSim`. The rawScore is near zero or negative. No bonus applies (mixed-case, not structural heading). The final score falls below `threshold = max(0.08, ...)` and the candidate is filtered out, returning `undefined`.\n    21→\n    22→The fundamental issue: **embeddings cannot distinguish \"dish named after its ingredients\" from \"fragment of an ingredient list\"**. The hard filters already make that distinction (ingredient lists have measurements, start with numbers, etc.), but their verdict is overruled by the embedding threshold.\n    23→\n    24→### Fix: Empty-pool fallback\n    25→\n    26→After the existing threshold filter (`let selected = scored.filter(s => s.score >= threshold)`), add a fallback:\n    27→\n    28→```typescript\n    29→// BEFORE (line ~389):\n    30→let selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n    31→\n    32→// AFTER:\n    33→let selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n    34→\n    35→// Empty-pool fallback: when threshold filtering discards every candidate,\n    36→// the hard filters' structural verdict should not be overruled by weak\n    37→// embedding differentiation. Return the best positional candidate.\n    38→if (selected.length === 0 && scored.length > 0) {\n    39→  // Prefer candidates near the top of the document (position 0 = most likely title).\n    40→  // Among ties, prefer higher score.\n    41→  const fallback = scored\n    42→    .slice()\n    43→    .sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position || b.score - a.score);\n    44→  selected = [fallback[0]];\n    45→}\n    46→```\n    47→\n    48→**Why this is safe:** Every candidate in `scored` already passed `passesHardFilters()` — no measurements, no metadata, no garbled text, not starting with a number, not lowercase-initial. If the entire pool of structurally-valid candidates has weak embedding differentiation, position is the strongest remaining signal (recipe titles appear at the top of the page). This fallback only fires when `selected` would otherwise be empty, so it cannot degrade any currently-passing test.\n    49→\n    50→### Expected behavior after fix\n    51→\n    52→- \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" is the only candidate in `scored` (the body text, ingredients, and metadata all fail hard filters).\n    53→- Threshold filter discards it (score < 0.08).\n    54→- Fallback selects it as the sole candidate → returns the correct title.\n    55→\n    56→---\n    57→\n    58→## Failure 2: \"Faszerowana papryka\" → `'PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM'`\n    59→\n    60→### Root Cause\n    61→\n    62→The first-line protection (lines 468–479) was designed for exactly this case: mixed-case title at position 0 followed by ALL_CAPS subtitle. But the protection runs **after** threshold filtering. The ALL_CAPS candidate \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" receives `+0.08` allCapsBonus + `+0.10` structuralBonus = `+0.18` on top of its rawScore. This inflates the threshold via `bestThresholdScore * 0.7`. The Polish mixed-case title \"Faszerowana papryka\" has a low rawScore (MiniLM is English-centric; short Polish text has low cosine similarity to the English TITLE_REFERENCE) and no bonuses. It falls below the inflated threshold, never enters `selected`, and the protection — which checks `selected.find(s => s.position === 0)` — silently becomes a no-op.\n    63→\n    64→The design is self-defeating: the protection requires the correct title to have already survived the threshold independently, but it's needed precisely when the title **cannot** survive the threshold.\n    65→\n    66→### Fix: Pre-threshold bilingual detection\n    67→\n    68→Move the bilingual detection to operate on the full `scored` array (before threshold filtering). When the pattern is detected, force-include the position-0 candidate and suppress the ALL_CAPS subtitle.\n    69→\n    70→```typescript\n    71→// BEFORE (lines 385-389):\n    72→const bestThresholdScore = Math.max(...scored.map((s) => s.thresholdScore));\n    73→const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7);\n    74→let selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n    75→\n    76→// AFTER:\n    77→// --- Pre-threshold bilingual title detection ---\n    78→// When a mixed-case candidate at position 0 is followed by a single ALL_CAPS\n    79→// candidate at position ≤ 2 in the FULL scored pool, this is a bilingual recipe\n    80→// page (e.g., Polish title + ALL_CAPS Korean romanization). Suppress the ALL_CAPS\n    81→// candidate before computing threshold so its bonuses don't inflate the threshold\n    82→// beyond the mixed-case title's reach.\n    83→//\n    84→// This replaces the post-threshold guard at lines 468-479 which was ineffective\n    85→// because it required both candidates to survive threshold independently.\n    86→let scoredForThreshold = scored;\n    87→const prePos0 = scored.find((s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text));\n    88→const preAllCaps = scored.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n    89→if (\n    90→  prePos0 &&\n    91→  preAllCaps.length === 1 &&\n    92→  preAllCaps[0].position <= 2\n    93→) {\n    94→  // Remove the ALL_CAPS subtitle from threshold computation AND from selection.\n    95→  scoredForThreshold = scored.filter((s) => s !== preAllCaps[0]);\n    96→}\n    97→\n    98→const bestThresholdScore = Math.max(...scoredForThreshold.map((s) => s.thresholdScore));\n    99→const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7);\n   100→let selected = scoredForThreshold.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n   101→```\n   102→\n   103→Then **remove or disable** the old post-threshold first-line protection (lines 468–479) since it's now redundant.\n   104→\n   105→**Why this is safe:**\n   106→- The guard condition is identical to the old one: mixed-case at position 0, exactly 1 ALL_CAPS candidate at position ≤ 2.\n   107→- `preAllCaps.length === 1` ensures it never fires on genuine multi-recipe pages (which have ≥ 2 ALL_CAPS headings).\n   108→- Moving it pre-threshold only changes behavior when the mixed-case title would otherwise be below threshold — which is precisely the failure case.\n   109→\n   110→### Expected behavior after fix\n   111→\n   112→- `scored` contains \"Faszerowana papryka\" (pos 0, mixed-case) and \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" (pos 1, ALL_CAPS).\n   113→- Pre-threshold detection identifies the bilingual pattern: pos0 is mixed-case, exactly 1 ALL_CAPS at pos ≤ 2.\n   114→- \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" is removed from `scoredForThreshold`.\n   115→- Threshold is now computed from \"Faszerowana papryka\" alone — much lower, achievable.\n   116→- \"Faszerowana papryka\" enters `selected` → returned as the title.\n   117→\n   118→---\n   119→\n   120→## Interaction between the two fixes\n   121→\n   122→The fixes are independent and non-conflicting:\n   123→\n   124→| Scenario | Fix 1 (fallback) | Fix 2 (bilingual) | Which fires? |\n   125→|---|---|---|---|\n   126→| Baked Eggs (sole candidate, below threshold) | Catches it | N/A (no ALL_CAPS) | Fix 1 |\n   127→| Faszerowana papryka (bilingual, threshold inflated) | Would also catch it as fallback | Prevents the problem entirely | Fix 2 (fix 1 is not needed) |\n   128→| Normal recipes (candidates above threshold) | Never fires | Never fires (no pattern match or >1 ALL_CAPS) | Neither |\n   129→| Multi-recipe ALL_CAPS pages | Never fires (candidates pass threshold) | Never fires (≥2 ALL_CAPS) | Neither |\n   130→\n   131→Fix 2 is the primary fix for failure 2. Fix 1 is the primary fix for failure 1. But fix 1 would also serve as a secondary safety net for failure 2 if fix 2 somehow didn't fire — defense in depth.\n   132→\n   133→---\n   134→\n   135→## Changes to make (ordered)\n   136→\n   137→### Change 1: Pre-threshold bilingual detection\n   138→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   139→**Location:** Before line 385 (threshold computation)\n   140→**Action:** Add bilingual detection on full `scored` array. Suppress the sole ALL_CAPS subtitle from threshold computation and selection when the pattern matches.\n   141→\n   142→### Change 2: Empty-pool fallback\n   143→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   144→**Location:** After line 389 (`let selected = scored.filter(...)`)\n   145→**Action:** Add fallback that selects the best positional candidate when `selected` is empty.\n   146→\n   147→### Change 3: Remove old post-threshold first-line protection\n   148→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   149→**Location:** Lines 468–479\n   150→**Action:** Remove the entire block. It's replaced by the pre-threshold version (change 1) and was ineffective in the failure case anyway.\n   151→\n   152→### No other changes needed\n   153→\n   154→- Hard filters: working correctly for both cases.\n   155→- Pre-merge continuation logic: working correctly (Baked Eggs candidate is correctly merged).\n   156→- Multi-title guard: not involved in either failure.\n   157→- Dedup logic: not involved in either failure.\n   158→- Structural heading detection: not involved in failure 1; correctly identifies PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM in failure 2 but this is handled by the bilingual guard.\n   159→\n   160→---\n   161→\n   162→## Risk Assessment\n   163→\n   164→**Risk of regression on passing tests:**\n   165→- **Low.** Fix 1 (fallback) only fires when `selected` is empty — this never happens for currently-passing tests. Fix 2 (bilingual) only fires when there's a mixed-case pos-0 with exactly 1 ALL_CAPS at pos ≤ 2 — this pattern doesn't appear in currently-passing tests (they have either 0 or ≥2 ALL_CAPS headings, or no mixed-case at pos 0).\n   166→\n   167→**Risk of over-fitting:**\n   168→- **Moderate but acceptable.** The bilingual guard is specific to a real pattern (bilingual cookbooks) rather than a one-off hack. The empty-pool fallback is a general safety net that addresses a genuine design gap (hard filters should not be overruled by weak embedding signals).\n   169→\n   170→**What could still go wrong:**\n   171→- A recipe where position 0 is genuinely not the title (e.g., book name on first line, recipe title on line 3). The fallback would return the wrong line. Mitigation: this is rare in the test corpus and the hard filters would likely catch book names (too long, or garbled).\n   172→- A recipe where position 0 is mixed-case and position 1 is ALL_CAPS but the ALL_CAPS line is the real title (not a subtitle). The bilingual guard would suppress it. Mitigation: the `position ≤ 2` and `length === 1` constraints are very specific.\n   173→\n   174→## Expected accuracy after changes\n   175→\n   176→- Iteration 8: 75% (6/8 passing, 2 failing)\n   177→- Projected: **100% (8/8 passing)** — both failures addressed with targeted, non-overlapping fixes.\n   178→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0144PXmjEmy913inJ4U8ScKn","session_id":"3e5c8568-eb2f-4e0e-8771-787e6907f7e7","uuid":"78327414-7ac6-4d54-a4a4-aeee6c7b1b7d"}
