{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01HtwnaDLVjhdR13kh4EKCAt","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01MM1C5J593z34kUhBfYNi4Y","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/10-d73df28/feedback.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2048,"cache_read_input_tokens":59383,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2048,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0144PXmjEmy913inJ4U8ScKn","session_id":"3e5c8568-eb2f-4e0e-8771-787e6907f7e7","uuid":"9701850c-0c55-41ee-bf5d-ccc1f6af0156"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YZ7knqAWfuSwdC21o74xCW","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 9 — Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Summary\n     4→\n     5→One failure remains: `Faszerowana papryka.real.txt`. The algorithm returns `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` (Korean romanization at position 1) instead of `Faszerowana papryka` (Polish title at position 0). The fix is a targeted relaxation of the bilingual detection guard — no other code paths need to change.\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## Root Cause Analysis\n    10→\n    11→### The bilingual detection condition is count-based when it should be position-based\n    12→\n    13→The pre-threshold bilingual suppression block (lines 390–395) was designed for exactly this pattern: a mixed-case title at position 0 followed by an ALL_CAPS foreign romanization at position ≤ 2. It correctly identifies `prePos0` (the mixed-case candidate at position 0) but then gates on `preAllCaps.length === 1` — requiring the *entire document* to contain exactly one ALL_CAPS candidate.\n    14→\n    15→This document has **four** ALL_CAPS candidates that pass `passesHardFilters`:\n    16→\n    17→| Candidate | Position | Role |\n    18→|---|---|---|\n    19→| `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` | 1 | Korean romanization (should be suppressed) |\n    20→| `NA 3 PAPRYKI` | 5 | Serving size |\n    21→| `SKŁADNIKI` | 9 | Section header |\n    22→| `WARZYWA` | 25 | Section header |\n    23→\n    24→Because `preAllCaps.length === 4`, the suppression does **not** fire. `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` enters scoring unsuppressed and accumulates +0.18 in bonuses (ALL_CAPS +0.08, structural heading +0.10) that overwhelm `Faszerowana papryka`'s position advantage.\n    25→\n    26→### Why this is a general pattern, not a one-off\n    27→\n    28→Polish recipe books routinely use ALL_CAPS for section headers (SKŁADNIKI, PRZYGOTOWANIE, WARZYWA) and serving info (NA 3 PAPRYKI). Any bilingual recipe page will have these alongside the foreign romanization, making `preAllCaps.length === 1` structurally impossible to satisfy. The count-based guard was written for a minimal case that doesn't occur in real documents.\n    29→\n    30→---\n    31→\n    32→## Proposed Fix\n    33→\n    34→### Replace count-based guard with positional + semantic check\n    35→\n    36→**Current code (lines 390–395):**\n    37→```typescript\n    38→const prePos0 = scored.find((s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text));\n    39→const preAllCaps = scored.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n    40→if (prePos0 && preAllCaps.length === 1 && preAllCaps[0].position <= 2) {\n    41→  const capsLower = preAllCaps[0].text.toLowerCase();\n    42→  scoredForThreshold = scored.filter((s) => !s.text.toLowerCase().startsWith(capsLower));\n    43→}\n    44→```\n    45→\n    46→**Proposed code:**\n    47→```typescript\n    48→const prePos0 = scored.find((s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text));\n    49→if (prePos0) {\n    50→  // Find ALL_CAPS candidates at position ≤ 2 (immediately after mixed-case title)\n    51→  const nearbyAllCaps = scored.filter(\n    52→    (s) => isAllCaps(s.text) && s.position >= 1 && s.position <= 2\n    53→  );\n    54→  // Check if any nearby ALL_CAPS candidate is semantically close to the position-0\n    55→  // candidate — indicating it's a translation/romanization of the same dish name.\n    56→  // Use the already-computed embeddings from rawScored.\n    57→  const pos0Embedding = rawScored.find((r) => r.text === prePos0.text)?.embedding;\n    58→  if (pos0Embedding) {\n    59→    const translationCandidates = nearbyAllCaps.filter((cap) => {\n    60→      const capEmbedding = rawScored.find((r) => r.text === cap.text)?.embedding;\n    61→      if (!capEmbedding) return false;\n    62→      const sim = cosineSimilarity(pos0Embedding, capEmbedding);\n    63→      return sim > 0.4;\n    64→    });\n    65→    if (translationCandidates.length > 0) {\n    66→      const suppressTexts = new Set(translationCandidates.map((t) => t.text.toLowerCase()));\n    67→      scoredForThreshold = scored.filter((s) => !suppressTexts.has(s.text.toLowerCase()));\n    68→    }\n    69→  }\n    70→}\n    71→```\n    72→\n    73→### Why this works\n    74→\n    75→1. **Positional check** (`position >= 1 && position <= 2`): Only considers ALL_CAPS candidates immediately after the mixed-case title. Section headers at position 9, 25 are irrelevant — they can't be bilingual translations of the title.\n    76→\n    77→2. **Semantic similarity check** (`cosineSimilarity > 0.4`): Both `Faszerowana papryka` and `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` are dish names. Their embeddings will be close because they refer to the same concept (a paprika dish). This distinguishes a translation from an unrelated ALL_CAPS line that happens to appear at position 1–2 (unlikely but possible).\n    78→\n    79→3. **No new embedding calls**: Both candidates already have embeddings computed in the rawScored pass. We reuse them, adding zero latency.\n    80→\n    81→4. **Suppression scope**: Only the translation candidate is removed from `scoredForThreshold` — all other candidates (including other ALL_CAPS section headers) remain in the pool. This is narrower and safer than the current approach which removes anything starting with the caps candidate's text.\n    82→\n    83→### What changes\n    84→\n    85→| Aspect | Before | After |\n    86→|---|---|---|\n    87→| Guard condition | `preAllCaps.length === 1` (global count) | `nearbyAllCaps` at position ≤ 2 (local) |\n    88→| Validation | None (position ≤ 2 only) | Position ≤ 2 AND embedding similarity > 0.4 |\n    89→| Suppression target | Anything starting with the single ALL_CAPS text | Exact match on confirmed translation candidates |\n    90→| Handles multiple section headers | No (breaks when count > 1) | Yes (ignores distant ALL_CAPS entirely) |\n    91→\n    92→### What does NOT change\n    93→\n    94→- Hard filters, candidate generation, merge logic — all untouched\n    95→- Scoring bonuses (ALL_CAPS +0.08, structural heading +0.10) — unchanged\n    96→- Dedup logic, multi-title guard, continuation join protection — unchanged\n    97→- Threshold computation formula — unchanged\n    98→- Empty-pool fallback — unchanged\n    99→\n   100→---\n   101→\n   102→## Edge Cases and Regression Safety\n   103→\n   104→### Case: Bilingual page with no section headers (original minimal case)\n   105→Before: `preAllCaps.length === 1` fires. After: `nearbyAllCaps` finds the same single candidate, similarity > 0.4 (both are dish names), suppression fires. **Same result.**\n   106→\n   107→### Case: ALL_CAPS title at position 0, mixed-case subtitle at position 1\n   108→`prePos0` requires `!isAllCaps(s.text)`, so if position 0 is ALL_CAPS, the block doesn't activate. **No change.**\n   109→\n   110→### Case: Mixed-case at position 0, unrelated ALL_CAPS at position 1\n   111→If the ALL_CAPS candidate at position 1 is semantically unrelated (e.g., \"SERVES 4\" that somehow passed filters), its embedding similarity to the position-0 candidate will be low (< 0.4). The block won't suppress it. **Safe.**\n   112→\n   113→### Case: No mixed-case at position 0\n   114→`prePos0` is undefined, entire block is skipped. **No change.**\n   115→\n   116→---\n   117→\n   118→## Similarity Threshold Justification (0.4)\n   119→\n   120→The threshold of 0.4 is deliberately low because:\n   121→- Two dish names referring to the same recipe (even in different languages) typically have cosine similarity 0.5–0.8 with MiniLM, because the food concept (paprika, eggs, etc.) overlaps strongly.\n   122→- A dish name vs. a section header (\"SKŁADNIKI\", \"PRZYGOTOWANIE\") typically has similarity 0.15–0.35, because they share no food-concept overlap.\n   123→- 0.4 sits cleanly in the gap between these distributions.\n   124→\n   125→If the gap turns out to be narrower for some language pairs, the threshold can be raised to 0.5 without losing this case (PAPRIKA/papryka share a cognate root, so similarity will be well above 0.5).\n   126→\n   127→---\n   128→\n   129→## Implementation Checklist\n   130→\n   131→1. Replace the bilingual detection block at lines 389–395 in `title-extractor.ts`\n   132→2. No new imports needed (`cosineSimilarity` already imported, `rawScored` embeddings already available)\n   133→3. No new embedding calls (zero performance impact)\n   134→4. Run existing test suite to confirm no regressions\n   135→5. Run title-loop evaluation to confirm `Faszerowana papryka` now returns correctly\n   136→\n   137→---\n   138→\n   139→## Expected Impact\n   140→\n   141→| Metric | Before | After |\n   142→|---|---|---|\n   143→| Passing cases | 7/8 (87.5%) | 8/8 (100%) |\n   144→| New embedding calls | 0 | 0 |\n   145→| Lines changed | ~6 lines replaced | ~15 lines replacement |\n   146→| Risk of regression | — | Low (strictly narrower suppression scope, with semantic validation gate) |\n   147→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0144PXmjEmy913inJ4U8ScKn","session_id":"3e5c8568-eb2f-4e0e-8771-787e6907f7e7","uuid":"560ae861-72f0-47b9-9c38-71ef10f68a07"}
