{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011zc13h66NoerwbKnXUfzFy","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 10 — Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Correction to Feedback Root Cause (Failure 1)\n     4→\n     5→The feedback states that \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" has 6 words and gets penalized by the pre-filter's `wordCount <= 5` sort. This is incorrect — the title has **5 words** (CHLEBEK, Z, WARZYWAMI, I, BOCZKIEM), so `wordCount(text) <= 5` is true and it sorts into the highest-priority tier alongside other short ALL_CAPS candidates. The pre-filter does not cut it.\n     6→\n     7→The actual root cause is a **structural heading mis-selection combined with dedup**:\n     8→\n     9→1. Both \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (position 1) and \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" (position 2) qualify as structural headings via `isStructuralHeading`.\n    10→2. `bestStructural` is selected by `rawScore`. If MiniLM rates \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" higher (plausible — it's a tighter food phrase that may embed closer to the title reference), it wins the structural heading slot.\n    11→3. `firstStructuralHeading` = \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\". The prefix filter at line 440 then removes prefixes of \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\", not prefixes of the real title.\n    12→4. \"CHLEBEK\" (position 8, a sub-section header for the bread part) is **not** a prefix of \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\", so it survives the prefix filter.\n    13→5. Dedup at line 489: \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" contains \"CHLEBEK\" (shorter) → the real title is removed. \"CHLEBEK\" wins.\n    14→\n    15→The prefix filter is structurally correct but depends on `bestStructural` being the real title — a precondition the algorithm cannot guarantee with cross-lingual embeddings.\n    16→\n    17→---\n    18→\n    19→## Fix 1: Polish Metadata Patterns in `looksLikeMetadata`\n    20→\n    21→### Root cause\n    22→Polish recipe conventions use patterns invisible to the English-only metadata regex:\n    23→- **Serving size**: \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" (for 3 peppers), \"NA OKOŁO 1 ½ KG\" (for about 1.5 kg), \"DLA 4 OSÓB\" (for 4 people)\n    24→- **Time metadata**: \"PRZYGOTOWANIE 1 GODZ. 45 MIN\", \"GOTOWANIE 30 MIN\", \"OCZEKIWANIE 1 GODZ. 30 MIN\"\n    25→- **OCR-corrupted time metadata**: \"PRZYGOTOWANTE 20 MIN\" (E→A), \"GOTOMANTE 15 MIN\" (OWANIE→MANTE)\n    26→\n    27→These survive all hard filters, enter the candidate pool, accumulate ALL_CAPS bonus, and compete with real titles.\n    28→\n    29→### Specific changes\n    30→\n    31→Add to `METADATA_PATTERNS` in `title-extractor.ts`:\n    32→\n    33→**Before:**\n    34→```typescript\n    35→const METADATA_PATTERNS = [\n    36→  /^(SERVES?|MAKES?|YIELDS?)\\b/i,\n    37→  /^(PREP(ARATION)?|COOK(ING)?|PROOF|RISING|FERMENTATION|REST(ING)?)\\s*(AND\\s*)?(COOK(ING)?)?\\s*TIME/i,\n    38→  /^SAMPLE\\s+SCHEDULE\\b/i,\n    39→  /^BULK\\s+FERMENTATION\\b/i,\n    40→  /^(THIS\\s+RECIPE\\s+)?MAKES\\b/i,\n    41→];\n    42→```\n    43→\n    44→**After:**\n    45→```typescript\n    46→const METADATA_PATTERNS = [\n    47→  /^(SERVES?|MAKES?|YIELDS?)\\b/i,\n    48→  /^(PREP(ARATION)?|COOK(ING)?|PROOF|RISING|FERMENTATION|REST(ING)?)\\s*(AND\\s*)?(COOK(ING)?)?\\s*TIME/i,\n    49→  /^SAMPLE\\s+SCHEDULE\\b/i,\n    50→  /^BULK\\s+FERMENTATION\\b/i,\n    51→  /^(THIS\\s+RECIPE\\s+)?MAKES\\b/i,\n    52→  // Polish serving-size patterns: \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\", \"NA OKOŁO 1 KG\", \"DLA 4 OSÓB\"\n    53→  /^NA\\s+(\\d|OKOŁO)\\b/i,\n    54→  /^DLA\\s+\\d/i,\n    55→  // Time-unit metadata: any line containing \"N MIN\" or \"N GODZ\" is prep/cook/rest time,\n    56→  // regardless of OCR-corrupted prefix (catches PRZYGOTOWANTE, GOTOMANTE, etc.)\n    57→  /\\b\\d+\\s*MIN\\b/i,\n    58→  /\\b\\d+\\s*GODZ/i,\n    59→];\n    60→```\n    61→\n    62→### Why time-unit patterns are safe as metadata filters\n    63→\n    64→Could `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN\\b` accidentally filter a legitimate recipe title? No:\n    65→- \"30 Minute Bread\" starts with a digit → already rejected by `startsWithNumber`\n    66→- \"MINESTRONE\" has \"MIN\" but no preceding digit → doesn't match\n    67→- \"5 MIN NOODLES\" starts with digit → already rejected\n    68→- In the entire 10-iteration test corpus, no legitimate title contains \"digit + MIN\" or \"digit + GODZ\"\n    69→\n    70→### Impact on test cases\n    71→\n    72→| Candidate | Pattern matched | Effect |\n    73→|---|---|---|\n    74→| \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" | `^NA\\s+\\d` | **Filtered** — fixes Failure 2 directly |\n    75→| \"NA OKOŁO 1 ½ KG\" | `^NA\\s+OKOŁO` | Filtered — correct for Kimchi input |\n    76→| \"DLA 4 OSÓB\" / \"DLA 4 OSOB\" | `^DLA\\s+\\d` | Filtered — reduces noise in CHLEBEK and MŁODE PORY |\n    77→| \"PRZYGOTOWANIE 1 GODZ. 45 MIN\" | `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN` (via \"45 MIN\") | Filtered |\n    78→| \"GOTOWANIE 30 MIN\" | `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN` | Filtered |\n    79→| \"OCZEKIWANIE 1 GODZ. 30 MIN\" | `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN` | Filtered |\n    80→| \"PRZYGOTOWANTE 20 MIN\" | `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN` | **Filtered** — catches OCR error |\n    81→| \"GOTOMANTE 15 MIN\" | `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN` | **Filtered** — catches OCR error |\n    82→| \"PIECZENIE 30 MINUT\" | `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN` | Filtered (hypothetical) |\n    83→| \"Leżakowanie\" | none (no digit) | Not filtered — correct |\n    84→\n    85→### Expected impact on Failure 2\n    86→\n    87→With \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" filtered as metadata, the candidates for \"Faszerowana papryka.real.txt\" become:\n    88→- \"Faszerowana papryka\" (position 0, mixed-case)\n    89→- \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" (position 1, ALL_CAPS)\n    90→- \"SKŁADNIKI\" (position 9, single-word ALL_CAPS)\n    91→- \"WARZYWA\" (position 25, single-word ALL_CAPS)\n    92→- Various body text joins\n    93→\n    94→The bilingual suppression correctly fires (position-0 mixed-case + position-1 ALL_CAPS with semantic similarity > 0.4). \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" is suppressed from threshold computation. \"Faszerowana papryka\" wins.\n    95→\n    96→---\n    97→\n    98→## Fix 2: Pre-dedup Sub-section Header Removal\n    99→\n   100→### Root cause\n   101→\n   102→The dedup rule at line 489 unconditionally prefers shorter candidates when one is a substring of another. This is correct for most cases (e.g., \"Pierogi Ruskie\" over \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki 3 ziemniaki\") but destructive when a short **sub-section header** shares words with the actual title.\n   103→\n   104→In the CHLEBEK case: \"CHLEBEK\" (position 8) is a sub-section header for the bread portion of the recipe. It is a substring of the actual title \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (position 1). The dedup rule removes the real title.\n   105→\n   106→The existing prefix filter at line 440 was designed to handle this, but it only removes prefixes of `firstStructuralHeading`. When `bestStructural` resolves to \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" instead of the real title (due to cross-lingual embedding noise), the prefix filter targets the wrong heading and \"CHLEBEK\" survives.\n   107→\n   108→### Specific changes\n   109→\n   110→Add a pre-dedup filter between the continuation join protection (line 482) and the dedup (line 489). The filter identifies **sub-section headers**: ALL_CAPS candidates that are followed in the source document by ingredient-like content.\n   111→\n   112→**Insert after line 482, before the dedup block:**\n   113→\n   114→```typescript\n   115→// Pre-dedup: remove sub-section headers that are substrings of other surviving candidates.\n   116→// A sub-section header is an ALL_CAPS candidate followed by ingredient-like lines in the source.\n   117→// Example: \"CHLEBEK\" (bread section header, followed by \"500 g mąki\") is a substring of\n   118→// \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (the real title). Without this filter, dedup kills the title.\n   119→selected = selected.filter((candidate) => {\n   120→  if (!isAllCaps(candidate.text)) return true;\n   121→  // Check if this candidate is followed by ingredient-like content\n   122→  const nextSourceLines = lines.slice(candidate.position + 1, candidate.position + 3);\n   123→  const followedByIngredients = nextSourceLines.some(\n   124→    (l) => looksLikeIngredient(l.trim()) || /^\\s*\\d/.test(l.trim())\n   125→  );\n   126→  if (!followedByIngredients) return true;\n   127→  // Only remove if a longer candidate contains this one as a substring\n   128→  const candidateLower = candidate.text.toLowerCase();\n   129→  const hasLongerParent = selected.some(\n   130→    (other) =>\n   131→      other !== candidate &&\n   132→      other.text.length > candidate.text.length &&\n   133→      other.text.toLowerCase().includes(candidateLower)\n   134→  );\n   135→  return !hasLongerParent;\n   136→});\n   137→```\n   138→\n   139→### Why this is safe\n   140→\n   141→The filter requires **three conditions** to fire simultaneously:\n   142→1. The candidate is ALL_CAPS\n   143→2. It is followed by ingredient-like lines (strong sub-section signal)\n   144→3. A longer candidate containing it as a substring also survived threshold\n   145→\n   146→This is conservative — it only resolves the specific conflict where a sub-section header's name overlaps with the title. It cannot remove standalone titles because condition (3) requires a longer superset candidate to exist.\n   147→\n   148→### Regression analysis\n   149→\n   150→| Test case | Effect |\n   151→|---|---|\n   152→| ARAYES SHRAK | \"ARAYES\" (1 word) doesn't survive threshold independently — never reaches dedup. No change. |\n   153→| Baked Eggs | No ALL_CAPS sub-section headers that are substrings of the title. No change. |\n   154→| CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM | **\"CHLEBEK\" removed** — followed by \"500 g mąki\" (ingredient) and is substring of real title. Fix applied. |\n   155→| Finnish Flatbreads | Two separate recipe titles, neither is a substring of the other. No change. |\n   156→| Faszerowana papryka | Already fixed by Fix 1 (NA 3 PAPRYKI filtered). No sub-section header conflict. No change. |\n   157→| MIXED SEED CRISPBREAD | No sub-section header conflicts. No change. |\n   158→| OVERNIGHT STRAIGHT PIZZA DOUGH | No sub-section header conflicts. No change. |\n   159→| SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS | No sub-section header conflicts. No change. |\n   160→| Kimchi z ogórków | \"SKŁADNIKI\" is ALL_CAPS and followed by ingredients, but no longer candidate contains \"SKŁADNIKI\". Condition (3) fails. No change. |\n   161→| MŁODE PORY DUSZONE W PIWIE | No ALL_CAPS sub-section headers that are substrings of the title. No change. |\n   162→\n   163→### Expected impact on Failure 1\n   164→\n   165→With Fix 1 removing \"DLA 4 OSÓB\", \"PRZYGOTOWANIE 1 GODZ. 45 MIN\", \"GOTOWANIE 30 MIN\", and \"OCZEKIWANIE 1 GODZ. 30 MIN\" from the candidate pool, the remaining ALL_CAPS candidates are:\n   166→- \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (position 1)\n   167→- \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" (position 2)\n   168→- \"CHLEBEK\" (position 8)\n   169→\n   170→Fix 1 alone helps by reducing noise, but the core CHLEBEK/dedup issue persists. Fix 2 then removes \"CHLEBEK\" because:\n   171→- It's ALL_CAPS ✓\n   172→- Followed by \"500 g mąki\" (ingredient) ✓\n   173→- \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" contains \"CHLEBEK\" and is longer ✓\n   174→\n   175→Similarly, \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" at position 2 is followed by \"500 g strączków zielonego groszku\" (ingredient) and is a substring of \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" — wait, no. Is \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" a substring of \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"? \"warzywa i boczek\" vs \"chlebek z warzywami i boczkiem\" — no, \"warzywami\" ≠ \"warzywa\". So condition (3) fails for \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\". It survives.\n   176→\n   177→Final candidates after Fix 2: \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" and \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\". The multi-title guard (line 504) fires with 2 ALL_CAPS candidates. `isSubHeader` checks if \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" (the non-first) is followed by ingredients → yes → `isSubHeader = true` → collapses to `[sortedCaps[0]]` = \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (position 1 < position 2).\n   178→\n   179→Result: **\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"** — correct.\n   180→\n   181→---\n   182→\n   183→## Fix 3: Structural Heading Selection Robustness (Optional)\n   184→\n   185→### Root cause\n   186→\n   187→`bestStructural` is chosen purely by `rawScore`, which depends on MiniLM cross-lingual embedding quality. For Polish text, the model may not reliably rank a 5-word compound title above a 3-word food phrase. This makes the downstream prefix filter fragile.\n   188→\n   189→### Specific changes\n   190→\n   191→Add a tiebreaker to `bestStructural` selection: when rawScores are within 0.03 of each other, prefer the candidate with more words (longer title = more specific = more likely the actual title, not a section header). If word counts are also equal, prefer the earlier position.\n   192→\n   193→**Before:**\n   194→```typescript\n   195→const bestStructural = structuralCandidates.length > 0\n   196→  ? structuralCandidates.reduce((a, b) => a.rawScore > b.rawScore ? a : b)\n   197→  : null;\n   198→```\n   199→\n   200→**After:**\n   201→```typescript\n   202→const bestStructural = structuralCandidates.length > 0\n   203→  ? structuralCandidates.reduce((a, b) => {\n   204→      const scoreDiff = a.rawScore - b.rawScore;\n   205→      if (Math.abs(scoreDiff) > 0.03) return scoreDiff > 0 ? a : b;\n   206→      // Tiebreak: more words (more specific) → better\n   207→      const wcDiff = wordCount(b.text) - wordCount(a.text);\n   208→      if (wcDiff !== 0) return wcDiff > 0 ? b : a;\n   209→      // Tiebreak: earlier position → better\n   210→      return a.position < b.position ? a : b;\n   211→    })\n   212→  : null;\n   213→```\n   214→\n   215→This makes the prefix filter at line 440 more likely to target the correct (longer, more specific) heading, providing defense-in-depth alongside Fix 2. With a 0.03 threshold, a clearly better rawScore still wins.\n   216→\n   217→### Risk assessment\n   218→\n   219→Low risk. Only changes behavior when two structural headings have nearly identical rawScores (within 0.03). In that case, preferring the longer/earlier candidate is almost always correct — a sub-section header is never the title when a longer heading containing the same topic exists.\n   220→\n   221→---\n   222→\n   223→## Summary\n   224→\n   225→| Fix | Addresses | Mechanism | Risk |\n   226→|---|---|---|---|\n   227→| **Fix 1**: Polish metadata patterns | Failure 2 directly; reduces Failure 1 noise | Hard filter in `looksLikeMetadata` | Very low — patterns are specific and well-attested |\n   228→| **Fix 2**: Pre-dedup sub-section removal | Failure 1 directly | Pre-dedup filter gated on 3 conditions | Low — conservative triple-condition gate |\n   229→| **Fix 3**: Structural heading tiebreaker | Failure 1 (defense-in-depth) | Tiebreaker with 0.03 threshold | Very low — only changes close-call decisions |\n   230→\n   231→### Expected accuracy after fixes\n   232→\n   233→All 8 existing test cases should pass. The 2 new test cases (Kimchi z ogórków, MŁODE PORY DUSZONE W PIWIE) should also benefit from the Polish metadata patterns.\n   234→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0144PXmjEmy913inJ4U8ScKn","session_id":"3e5c8568-eb2f-4e0e-8771-787e6907f7e7","uuid":"21da97e6-903c-40a6-88a4-b85c07b40b64"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HjceNqa9qPaHhBNTEq4BZn","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 11 Failure Analysis\n     2→\n     3→## Failure: CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\n     4→\n     5→**Expected:** `CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM`\n     6→**Got:** `CHLEBEK`\n     7→\n     8→**Input structure (key lines):**\n     9→```\n    10→idx 0:  Lato | Dania główne                      ← book category header (\"Summer | Main dishes\")\n    11→idx 1:  CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM           ← actual recipe title (5 words, ALL_CAPS)\n    12→idx 2:  WARZYWA I BOCZEK                         ← section header (\"Vegetables and Bacon\")\n    13→idx 3:  500 g strączków zielonego groszku        ← ingredient (starts with number)\n    14→idx 4:  1 żółta papryka                          ← ingredient\n    15→...\n    16→idx 8:  CHLEBEK                                  ← section header (\"Bread\")\n    17→idx 9:  500 g mąki                               ← ingredient (starts with number)\n    18→...\n    19→```\n    20→\n    21→---\n    22→\n    23→## Root Cause: False Positive in Bilingual Title Detection\n    24→\n    25→### What the bilingual detection is supposed to do\n    26→\n    27→The bilingual detection at lines 409–431 targets a specific page layout: a **mixed-case title in language A** at position 0, followed immediately by an **ALL_CAPS romanization/translation** at positions 1–2. It suppresses the ALL_CAPS candidate from the threshold calculation so the original mixed-case title can win.\n    28→\n    29→### Why it misfires here\n    30→\n    31→`prePos0` = `\"Lato | Dania główne\"` — This line passes the check: it is at position 0 and is not ALL_CAPS.\n    32→\n    33→However, `\"Lato | Dania główne\"` is not a recipe title at all. It is a **book chapter header** meaning \"Summer | Main dishes\". It marks the section of the cookbook, not a recipe.\n    34→\n    35→`nearbyAllCaps` = candidates at positions 1–2:\n    36→- `\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"` (position 1)\n    37→- `\"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\"` (position 2)\n    38→\n    39→The algorithm then computes cosine similarity between `\"Lato | Dania główne\"` and each of these. Both are Polish food-related texts. In a multilingual embedding space, food-domain terms share enough semantic neighbourhood that the similarity of `\"Summer | Main dishes\"` to `\"BREAD WITH VEGETABLES AND BACON\"` can exceed the 0.4 threshold.\n    40→\n    41→When one or both are identified as `translationCandidates`, the filter:\n    42→```javascript\n    43→scoredForThreshold = scored.filter((s) => {\n    44→  const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n    45→  return !translationCandidates.some((t) => sLower.startsWith(t.text.toLowerCase()));\n    46→});\n    47→```\n    48→also removes the 2-line join `\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM WARZYWA I BOCZEK\"` (it starts with the suppressed text). The result is that **all longer ALL_CAPS candidates anchored at position 1 are purged from `scoredForThreshold`** — and therefore from `selected`.\n    49→\n    50→### The cascade after suppression\n    51→\n    52→With `\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"` absent from `selected`:\n    53→\n    54→1. **Prefix removal doesn't fire** (lines 458–466). The guard is `if (firstStructuralHeading && selected.some((s) => s.text === firstStructuralHeading.text))`. `firstStructuralHeading` may point to `\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"` from `rawScored` (embedding quality), but it is not in `selected`, so the condition is false. `\"CHLEBEK\"` is never removed as a prefix.\n    55→\n    56→2. **Pre-dedup section filter cannot act** (lines 506–523). The filter correctly identifies `\"CHLEBEK\"` (position 8) as an ALL_CAPS candidate followed by an ingredient line (`\"500 g mąki\"` starts with a number). But the filter only removes `\"CHLEBEK\"` when a longer candidate containing it exists in `selected`. Since `\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"` was suppressed, `hasLongerParent = false`. `\"CHLEBEK\"` survives.\n    57→\n    58→3. **Dedup rule** (shorter wins) has nothing to act on — `\"CHLEBEK\"` is the only ALL_CAPS survivor in the upper portion of the document.\n    59→\n    60→4. **Multi-title guard** sees `\"CHLEBEK\"` as the first (or only) surviving ALL_CAPS candidate and returns it.\n    61→\n    62→Result: `\"CHLEBEK\"` — the bread sub-section header — is returned instead of the recipe title.\n    63→\n    64→---\n    65→\n    66→## Why Previous Fix Was Insufficient\n    67→\n    68→Iteration 10 identified the pre-dedup section filter (lines 506–523) and the prefix removal step (lines 458–466) as mechanisms to handle the `\"CHLEBEK\"` / `\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"` conflict. Both mechanisms are correct **when the full title is present in `selected`**. The iteration 10 fix correctly handles the 25-candidate cap issue (the full title now has 5 words, fitting the `wordCount <= 5` priority tier). But neither fix anticipated the bilingual detection suppressing the full title before either mechanism gets a chance to act.\n    69→\n    70→---\n    71→\n    72→## Common Themes\n    73→\n    74→### 1. Book category headers are indistinguishable from recipe titles by position\n    75→\n    76→`\"Lato | Dania główne\"` (\"Summer | Main dishes\") appears at position 0 and passes all hard filters. The algorithm has no concept of \"chapter header\" vs \"recipe title\". The bilingual detection triggers on it as if it were a foreign-language recipe title, suppressing the real title two lines below.\n    77→\n    78→### 2. Bilingual detection uses a 0.4 similarity threshold that is too permissive for food content\n    79→\n    80→The bilingual detection was designed for clearly-paired translations (e.g., Korean title → ALL_CAPS romanization). The 0.4 threshold is calibrated for cross-lingual translation, but within Polish food text, `\"Summer | Main dishes\"` and `\"BREAD WITH VEGETABLES AND BACON\"` may share enough domain vocabulary to exceed it. This causes the correction mechanism to fire on a completely unrelated pair.\n    81→\n    82→### 3. Cascading dependency on full title presence\n    83→\n    84→Multiple downstream safety mechanisms (prefix removal at line 458, pre-dedup filter at line 506) are gated on the full title being present in `selected`. They are not independently robust — they share the same precondition. One upstream suppression (bilingual detection) disables both simultaneously, leaving no fallback.\n    85→\n    86→### 4. Section headers as recipe title candidates\n    87→\n    88→`\"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\"` and `\"CHLEBEK\"` are cookbook sub-section headers (ingredient groups for the two components of the recipe). They resemble recipe titles structurally: short, ALL_CAPS, Polish food words. The algorithm cannot distinguish them from standalone recipe titles without knowing the document structure. The document structure (each section header immediately followed by its ingredient list) is the necessary signal, and while the multi-title guard and pre-dedup filter attempt to use it, both are blocked by the earlier suppression.\n    89→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0144PXmjEmy913inJ4U8ScKn","session_id":"3e5c8568-eb2f-4e0e-8771-787e6907f7e7","uuid":"aa8d8082-c713-4447-9feb-01f977181f3c"}
