{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01HJfpAfgV6GHKwNRSDRkoWa","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive understanding of the problem. Let me think about the key proposed changes.\n\nThe single failure is: CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM → returns \"CHLEBEK\"\n\nRoot cause: The bilingual detection at lines 409-431 falsely triggers on \"Lato | Dania główne\" (book category header) at position 0, treating it as a mixed-case title. It then compares it with nearby ALL_CAPS candidates and suppresses them as \"translations\", removing the actual title from the pool.\n\nLet me think about what fixes would work:\n\n**Fix 1: Recognize category headers with pipe separators**\n\n\nThe pipe character is a dead giveaway for category headers like \"Season | Category\" and almost never appears in recipe titles. I can add a check to skip lines containing pipes when evaluating position-0 mixed-case candidates for bilingual detection.\n\n**Fix 2: Tighten bilingual detection to require actual translation similarity**\nThe 0.4 threshold is too permissive for same-language food content. Raising it to 0.5 or 0.6 would help, though I need to verify it doesn't break the Faszerowana papryka case where the threshold is actually needed.\n\nLet me reconsider the bilingual detection flow more carefully. The algorithm finds a mixed-case candidate at position 0, then looks for ALL_CAPS candidates at positions 1-2, and suppresses them if their cosine similarity exceeds 0.4. The problem is that \"Lato | Dania główne\" passes the position-0 check, \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" is ALL_CAPS, and they're similar enough in the food domain to trigger suppression. The cleanest solution is to exclude position-0 candidates that contain pipes, since those are clearly category headers rather than titles.\n\nBut I should think about whether there's a more robust approach. The bilingual detection was built for a specific pattern—Korean romanization following Polish text—but it's firing on unrelated pairs now. I could raise the similarity threshold from 0.4, though I'd need to verify what the actual similarity is for the legitimate Faszerowana papryka case. Or I could make the position-0 candidate pass a title-likeness check: no pipes, reasonable word count, not metadata. There's also the option of making downstream logic more resilient to false positives.\n\nThe cleanest fix is probably a combination: hard-filter lines with pipe separators since they're clearly category headers, not titles. Then tighten bilingual detection to require the position-0 candidate to actually score well as a title, not just avoid being all caps. And add a safety check so bilingual suppression doesn't kill the best structural heading. If I just filter out category headers upfront, that might solve it entirely.\n\nBut I should also consider whether there's a deeper structural problem here—multiple mechanisms are cascading on the full title being present. Looking at the pre-dedup section filter logic...\n\nActually, what if that filter checked against all candidates in `rawScored` rather than just the selected ones? That way even if the full title got suppressed, the filter could still detect it exists and remove the substring. Combined with excluding category headers from bilingual detection and adding a guard to preserve the first structural heading, this gives us multiple independent layers of protection against this kind of suppression cascade.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1058,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4929,"cache_read_input_tokens":32875,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4929},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3e5c8568-eb2f-4e0e-8771-787e6907f7e7","uuid":"cc255374-8fc6-4647-bb33-352257f48575"}
